Part One : Relationship between two categorical variables

Vigorous Activity Proportion by Education Attainment

Two-way table

A two way table displays a categorical variable broken down by another categorical variable. In this example vigorous_activity (response variable) is broken down by education (explanatory variable). Which means we are assessing if the proportion of participation in a vigorous activity varies across educational levels. We will use the tabyl function that you are already familiar with. When using tably with 2 variables, the first input is typically the explanatory variable and the second input is the response variable. Note how the levels for vigorous_activity dont have any reference (yes to what, one may ask). To provide more details you can add a header above your tables columns.

demo %>%
  
  tabyl( education, vigorous_activity) %>%
    adorn_totals(c("row")) %>% 
    adorn_percentages("row") %>% 
    adorn_pct_formatting(digits=0) %>% 
  
  kable() %>%
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped",
                  full_width = T, 
                  position="left")
education yes no refused dont know NA_
not hs grad 42% 58% 0% 0% 0%
hs grad 45% 55% 0% 0% 0%
post hs 40% 60% 0% 0% 0%
bachelors 38% 62% 0% 0% 0%
adv degree 36% 64% 0% 0% 0%
dont know 0% 100% 0% 0% 0%
Total 40% 60% 0% 0% 0%

Adding header above response variables levels

The argument add_header_above() will print a header above your columns, but you will need to specify the number of columns, in this case there are 6. The c(",vigorous_activity"=5) says leave the first column blank (since it already has a header of education) and place the header vigorous_activity above the remaining 5 columns of yes, no, refused, dont know and NA_.

demo %>%
  
  tabyl( education, vigorous_activity) %>%
    adorn_totals(c("row")) %>% 
    adorn_percentages("row") %>% 
    adorn_pct_formatting(digits=0) %>% 
  
  kable(booktabs = TRUE) %>%
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped",
                  full_width = T, 
                  position="left") %>% 
    add_header_above(c("","vigorous activity"=5))

Filtering observations

After you have created the basic table you might want to filter by your categorical variables levels to improve the readability of the table. vigorous_activity has unncessary levels of dont know and refused, so I removed them by filtering for just the levels of yes and no using filter(vigorous_activity %in% c("yes","no")) the %in% operator along with c() function allow you to filter for a list of desired levels. filter(!vigorous_activity %in% c("don't know","refused")) would also have worked, although you would have to add a second filter of filter(!is.na(vigorous_activity)) (You will probably find it easier to filter the levels that you want, although it might take more typing of levels.)

Note: the change in add_header_above , since now there are only 3 columns in my table.

demo %>%
  
  filter(vigorous_activity %in% c("yes","no") &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 

  
  tabyl( education, vigorous_activity) %>%
    adorn_totals(c("row")) %>% 
    adorn_percentages("row") %>% 
    adorn_pct_formatting(digits=0) %>% 
  
  kable(booktabs = TRUE) %>%
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped", full_width = T, 
                position="left") %>% 
    add_header_above(c("","vigorous activity"= 2))

Total 40% 60%

Bar Graph to accompany table

Having a graphic accompany your two way table will add a visual aspect to yout analysis. Since our variables are both categorical we will use geom_bar to construct a bar graph. There are many options for a type of bar graph. For more details on options see R for Data Wrangling : Barplot. For a bar graph with 2 categorical variables, the explanatory variables is the x variable, while the **response* variable is used to fill in the bars. In order to match the Yes/No order in my table, I usd the argument position = position_fill(reverse = TRUE) in the geom_bar layer. The scale_y_continuous(labels=percent) argument changes the scaling of my measurement axis (Note: It is initially the y-axis, but after coord_flip() it becomes the x-axis).

demo %>%
  
  filter(vigorous_activity %in% c("yes","no") &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x=education, fill=vigorous_activity)) +
    geom_bar(position = position_fill(reverse = T), width=.6) +
  
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2") +
    scale_y_continuous(labels=percent) +
    coord_flip()

Part Two : Grouping by a third categorical variable

Often you will want to see the relationship between two categorical variables when your observations are grouped by a third variables and then tabulated separately. For this example, we are grouping the observations by gender and then creating a two-way table for each gender. This is to see if the trends between vigorous_activity and education hold across genders. In order to do this, 2 two-way tables are constructed, one for each level of third categorical variable (in this case 2 levels, male and female). An additional filter command will allow one to create tables for each level of the third categorical variable. Since our third variable is gender we will insert filter(gender == "male") to filter out all observations where gender is male.

Constructing Tables

Male Responses

demo %>% 
  filter(gender =="male") %>% 

  filter(vigorous_activity %in% c("yes","no") &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  tabyl(education, vigorous_activity) %>% 
    adorn_totals(c("row")) %>% 
    adorn_percentages("row") %>% 
    adorn_pct_formatting(digits=0) %>% 
  
  kable(booktabs = TRUE) %>%
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped",
                  full_width = T, 
                  position="left") %>%
    add_header_above(c("MALE RESPONSES \n \n vigorous activity"=3))

Faceted Bar Plots

Method of construction is similar to the earlier example of bar plot for two categorical variables. THe addition of the facet_wrap argument, will create barplots for each level of the third categorical variable. In order to look at barplots of hrs_work_week for different educational levels, we add a plot layer facet_wrap(~ gender, ncol = 1). The ~ gender define the variable to facet by in the barplots. The ncol = 1 argument sets the output of barplots into one column.

demo %>%
  
  filter(vigorous_activity %in% c("yes","no") &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 

  ggplot(aes(x=education, fill=vigorous_activity)) +
    geom_bar(position = position_fill(reverse = TRUE), width=.6) +
    
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2") +
    facet_wrap(~gender, ncol=1) +
    ggtitle("Engaging in a Vigorous Activity (24h) comparison with Education Level\n Grouped by Gender") +
    scale_y_continuous(labels=percent) +
    coord_flip()

Narrative Summary

When looking at the all addhealth4observations, the percent of those who engaging in vigorous activity in the past 24 hours decreases as education level increases, showing a potential association. When comparing vigorous activity with gender, 49% of men responsed with yes, compared to 33% for women, for difference in sample proportions of 16%. The relationship between vigorous activiy and education level was different for men and women. The earlier trend of vigorous activity decreasing and education level increases is observed for men, but for women the trends is not observed.

Part Three: Relationship between numerical and categorical variables

Analysis of Relationship between Educational Level and Usual Hours Worked Per Week

Participants in the study were asked" How many hours a week (do/did) you usually work at this job? in reference to their current or most recent job. We are investigating if there is a relationship between hour worked and education level. We will start with a summary statistics on hour worked grouped by education level, then well create a visual that best captures the relationship and/or difference among education levels.

Summary Statistics

For summary statistics, we use the summarize function again. This time well add the argument group_by(education), which will calculate summary statistics within each level of the education variable.

demo %>% 
  
  filter(hrs_work_week < 121 &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  group_by(education) %>%
  
  summarize(n = n(),
            min = min(hrs_work_week),
            q1 = quantile(hrs_work_week, probs=0.25),
            median = median(hrs_work_week),
            mean = round(mean(hrs_work_week),1),
            q3 = quantile(hrs_work_week, probs=0.75),
            max = max(hrs_work_week),
            sd = round(sd(hrs_work_week),1)) %>% 
  
  kable() %>% 
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped",
                  full_width = T, 
                  position="left")   %>% 
    add_header_above(c("hours worked summary statistics "= 9))
hours worked summary statistics
education n min q1 median mean q3 max sd

hs grad 805 10 40 40 41.1 45 120 11.1
post hs 2183 10 37 40 40.5 45 120 11.6
bachelors 1246 10 40 40 41.9 45 106 10.8
adv degree 414 10 40 40 43.5 50 80 11.2

Visualization

There are several options to choose from when visually inspecting the relationship between a numerical and categorical variable. Your summary statistics provide numerical values to compare across the categorical variable, while your visualization provide an opportunity to see difference in the overall distribution.

Faceting

Faceting is used when wed like to create small multiples of the same plot over a different categorical variable. By default, all of the small multiples will have the same vertical axis.

For example, suppose we were interested in looking at whether usual hour worked varied by the educational level. This is what is meant by the distribution of one variable over another variable: hrs_work_week is response variable and education is the explanatory variable. In order to look at histograms of hrs_work_week for different educational levels, we add a plot layer facet_wrap(~ education, ncol = 1). The ~ education define the variable to facet by in the histograms. The ncol = 1 argument sets the output of histograms into one column. The addition of the aesthetic fill=education gives each faceted histogram a color corresponding to its educational level.

Faceted Histogram

demo %>% 
  
  filter(hrs_work_week < 121 &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(hrs_work_week))+
  
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..,
                       fill=education), 
                   color="white", 
                   binwidth = 5) +
  
      scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2") +
  
    facet_wrap(~ education, 
               ncol=1,
               as.table = FALSE)  ## reverses the order of the levels to match boxplots

Faceted Density Plot

Density plot is a computed smoothed version of the histogram (note: the adjust argument changes how the smoothing is calculated). This is a useful alternative to the histogram for continuous data that comes from an underlying smooth distribution. Also note how the aesthetics and structure are similar to the histogram.

demo %>% 
  
  filter(hrs_work_week < 121 &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(hrs_work_week)) +
  
    geom_density(aes(fill=education), 
                 color="white",
                 adjust=2) +
  
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2") +
  
    facet_wrap(~ education, 
               ncol=1,
               as.table = FALSE)  ## reverses the order of the levels to match boxplots

Boxplots

While histograms can help to show the distribution of data, boxplots have much more flexibility, and can provide even more information in a single graph. The y aesthetic is the numeric variable you want to include in the boxplot, and the x aesthetic is a grouping variable. For instance, below we set education as the aesthetic mapping for x, and hrs_work_week as the aesthetic mapping for y. This creates a boxplot of the usaul hours worked per week for different levels of education. The aesthetic fill argument is not necessary, but assigns color for each levels boxplot (which should match your grouping* or x** variable.

demo %>% 
  
  filter(hrs_work_week < 121 &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(y=hrs_work_week, x=education))+
  
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2") +
  
    geom_boxplot(aes(fill=education)) +
  
    coord_flip()  # might be nice to re-scale axis ( to see middle 50 better)

Violin Plots

A violin plot is a compact display of a continuous distribution. It is a blend of geom_boxplot() and geom_density(): a violin plot is a mirrored density plot displayed in the same way as a boxplot. Note how the aesthetics are similar to the geom_boxplot. Adding the draw_quantiles=c(0.25,0.5,.75) argument draws Q1, median and Q3.

demo %>% 
  
  filter(hrs_work_week < 121 &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(y=hrs_work_week, x=education)) +
  
    geom_violin(aes(fill=education),
                draw_quantiles=c(0.25,0.5,.75),
                adjust=2) +
  
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2") +
  
    coord_flip()

Density curves for each level on the same plot

Sometimes, you might want to directly compare the density curves for each level on the same plot. Set ggplots aesthetic color= education (which is my categorical variable). You can also set your x-axiss limits with the argument xlim(). In this example the x-axis limits are set from 10 to 80 hours. xlim and ylim can be used on most geoms.

demo %>% 
  
  filter(hrs_work_week < 121 &
         education %in% c("not hs grad", "hs grad", "post hs", "bachelors", "adv degree")) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x=hrs_work_week, color=education)) +
  
    geom_density(alpha = 0.1, adjust=2) +
  
    xlim(10, 80) +
  
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2") 
## Warning: Removed 32 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Narrative Summary

Our summary statistics show that the median is 40 hours worked for each education level. The mean hour worked does slightly increase as we move up to adv degree having the largest mean of 43.5 hours. not hs grad and adv degree have the larger IQRs of 9 and 10 hours respectively, while not a hs grad has the largest standard deviation of 12.7 hours. This all means thatnot hs grad and adv degree exhibit greater variation in hours works from our 5 education levels.

The boxplot shows similar details that were noticed in the summary statistics. The histogram allows us to see that all distribution are extremely uni-modal at 40 hours. The distributions are fairly symmetrical, with a slight secondary bulge around 50 hours for most education levels. There are not too many observations past 60 hours of work, although maximum reported hours hit 120 hours.

Boxplot

In order to include an additional categorical variable add the aesthetic color=gender to your ggplot command. This will split each educational level by gender.

demo %>% 
  
  filter(hrs_work_week < 121) %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(y=hrs_work_week, x=education, color=gender))+
  
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2") +
  
    geom_boxplot() +
  
    coord_flip()  # might be nice to re-scale axis ( to see middle 50 better)

Narrative Summary

When we look closer at usual hours worked by education level, but now grouped by gender - there are some interesting observations. For each level of education the mean hours for women is less than that of men. The difference in the range of middle 50% can be seen in the boxplot above. Only when we examine adv degree do we see the middle 50% observations align with eachother across gender.
